{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:55:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:55:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17486"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10176"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10176"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5388"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA new screening test for diabetes is being evaluated. In a study of 1000 patients, 200 have confirmed diabetes based on glucose tolerance testing. The new screening test correctly identifies 180 of these patients as having diabetes, but misses 20 cases. The test also incorrectly identifies 100 people without diabetes as having the condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the sensitivity of this screening test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["90%","64%","87%","82%","97%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esensitivity of 90%\u003C/strong\u003E is calculated by dividing the number of true positives (180) by the total number of patients who actually have diabetes (200).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E64%\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the positive predictive value (180/280)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E87%\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the specificity (700/800)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E97%\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the negative predictive value (700/720)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate sensitivity:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETrue Positives = 180\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFalse Negatives = 20\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensitivity = True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensitivity = 180 / 200 = 0.90 or 90%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA highly sensitive test like this one (90%) is particularly useful for ruling out disease when the result is negative, as it has a low false negative rate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sensitivity is the proportion of true positive cases correctly identified by a test out of all cases that truly have the condition.","A highly sensitive test is most useful for ruling out disease when negative (SnOUT rule).","Sensitivity is calculated as: True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives)"],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},